PhD Thesis

Bounds of Accelerated Planetary Engineering: A Stochastic Systems Architecture for Partial Planetary Engineering (PPE) on Mars

Candidate: [Your Name]
Department: Systems Engineering / Aerospace Engineering
Institution: [Your University]
Date: [Current Date]

---

Abstract

Traditional estimates for Mars terraforming range from 100,000 to 1,000,000 years, rendering the concept operationally irrelevant for near-term strategic planning. Recent speculative literature suggests exponential technologies could compress this timeline to decades, but these claims lack validation against thermodynamic limits, volatile inventory constraints, and logistical failure modes. This research establishes the physical and logistical lower bounds of Partial Planetary Engineering (PPE)—defined as achieving liquid water stability and ~300 mbar atmospheric pressure without full human breathability. By integrating Energy Balance Models (EBM), resource-constrained Von Neumann kinetics with stochastic failure, and a Logistics Readiness Levels (LRL) framework validated via expert elicitation, this thesis quantifies the minimum viable breakthroughs required for habitability within human-relevant timelines. A novel System-of-Systems (SoS) simulation framework is developed, coupling thermodynamic, kinetic, and logistical sub-models. Nondimensionalization of the governing equations reveals that system behavior is governed by nine independent Pi groups. Monte Carlo simulations using Latin Hypercube Sampling across these groups demonstrate that the dominant constraint is energy density (Π₇), not replication speed. The results indicate that while a 10‑year timeline is physically impossible under known constraints, a 100‑year PPE campaign is feasible only if autonomous manufacturing failure rates remain below 0.1% per cycle and energy density exceeds 50 W/kg. This work provides a validated decision tool for policymakers to distinguish feasible engineering pathways from physical impossibilities.

